TY  - JOUR
T1  - Do the Burdens to Being Public Affect the Investment and Innovation of Newly Public Firms?
AU  - Dambra, Michael
AU  - Gustafson, Matthew
Y1  - 2020/04/21
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3436
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3436
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 594
EP  - 616
VL  - 67
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We examine how regulatory burdens affect the investment and innovation of newly public firms. To do so, we exploit the Jumpstart Our Business Startups (JOBS) Act, which eliminates certain disclosure, auditing, and governance requirements for a subset of newly public firms. Firms treated with these reduced burdens invest more and more efficiently after going public relative to untreated firms. These findings are concentrated in innovative investments and are nonexistent in dual-class firms. Overall, our findings suggest that the burdens to being public exacerbate agency frictions, which lead managers to take on fewer risky projects.This paper was accepted by Suraj Srinivasan, accounting.
